<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,727,752]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Comments:</emphasis>
While known from only three females, the notal pattern of 
<taxonomicName box="[1051,1318,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivittatum">
<emphasis box="[1051,1318,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Allometopon bivittatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique enough within the genus to justify description, consisting of two dark, broad postsutural stripes (fused on basal half in 
<typeStatus box="[180,283,799,824]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">holotype</typeStatus>
). A relatively long anterior dorsocentral and two small pairs of lateral scutellars are also diagnostic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
